ter death and that deceased non-Mormon family members can \tbe baptized by proxy and thus join their relatives in the \thereafter.  Because of these beliefs Mormons have been \tconsidered outcasts by mainline Christian denominations and \tas heretics by religious fundamentalists. \t \tJoseph Smith was a controversial figure in his day -- he was \tboth worshiped as a saint and denounced as a fraud.  Because \tof persecution he led his band of loyal followers from \tPalmyra New York westward to Ohio and then to Illinois \twhere in 1844 he was shot to death by an agry mob.  Brigham \tYoung who reportedly had as many as eighty wives took over \tthe leadership of the church and led the Mormons further \twestward to found the new Zion in Salt Lake City.  \tFollowing the teachings of Joseph Smith in the practice of \tpolygamy was perhaps the Mormons most controversial practice \tin nineteenth-century America. \t \tWhile other religions go back many centuries -- \tMuhammadanism 1200 years; Christianity 2000; and Judaism \t3000 -- and attempts to examine their beginnings are \tdifficult extensive historical investigation of Mormon \troots is possible.  Some Mormons are willing to examine this \thistory objectively bu others maintain that such scrutiny \tis dangerous to the faith. \t \tIn the following pages _Free Inquiry_ presents two articles \tabout the Mormon church.  First George D. Smith a lifelong \tmember of the church provides a detailed critical \texamination of Joseph Smith and his claim the the _Book of \tMormon_ was divinely revealed.  Second we present a portion \tof an interview with philosopher Sterling McMurrin also a \tMormon since birth
